	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>April 12<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1858</date></p>
				<p>My dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Your esteemed favor of <date>29<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> ultimo<lb/> duly came to hand&#59; as did also the Package of Books&#8212;<lb/> the contents of which were distributed strictly in accordance<lb/> with your instructions.  <persName>M. S. Friend</persName> declined taking the<lb/> Occident to his address&#44; saying he was not a subscriber&#44; and<lb/> I regret to say&#44; <persName>Boyds</persName> carrier returned one Number from which<lb/> he had lost the direction and it is impossible for me to tell<lb/> to whom it belongs&#44; although I will endeavor to find out<lb/> <persName>Mr B. Cohen</persName> has paid his bill of &#36;6. as has also a Bijin<lb/> paid his of &#36;2.50.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I send by <persName>Adams &#38; Co.</persName> the package received last month<lb/> from <persName>J. Hart Senr</persName> of <placeName>Charleston</placeName>&#44; having found no private<lb/> opportunity to which I could send it.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have read the last number of the Occident with unusual<lb/> interest&#44; more particularly the portions relating to your good self<lb/> personally.  I had not previously any just conception of the<lb/> extent of your persecutions by Secret for who seem to have had<lb/> no scruples as to the means used to inflict injury &#38; <hi rend="underline">insult</hi>.<lb/>  I hope however you will soon triumph over them all and<lb/> make them bite the dust.</p>
				<p>With kindest regards to <persName>Mrs Cozens</persName> &#38; the young ladies.</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I remain Dr Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours sincerely</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">Hanford</persName></p>
			
